Mid-Term Project

Overview

  • Use Medicare CCLF Claims from Syntegra dataset to answer key business questions
  • Extra credit for building up on the questions below (additional questions + answers)
  • One Jupyter notebook solution with clear Python code and all cell outputs available
  • At least two data quality checks

Step 0. Prepare raw input datasets

Here we will 1) load original datasets, 2) remove unused columns, 3) de-duplicate rows, and 4) join datasets, not necessarily in this order

Assumptions:

  • Claim ID (cur_clm_uniq_id) represents one claim, which may or may not have more than one code (code could be HCPCS/CPT, diagnosis, procedure...)
  • There is a one-to-many relationship between patient IDs (bene_mbi_id) and claim IDs (cur_clm_uniq_id), i.e. each claim is unique to one patient, but one patient can have more than one claim

Q1. Based on the trends for the share of CVM claims as a percentage of total claims over the years 2016 through 2018, what are some business insights you can gather? What are some additional analyses you could do based on these trends?

Analysis

As we can see in the horizontal bar graph, we can see that the CVM takes up a big portion of the current claims. As CVM is the 2nd largest from the total claims, we can observe that CVM are already one of the largely focused area in the medical and pharmaceutical industry. However, we can also observe from the stacked bar graph that CVM claims is steadily growing in terms of proportion of total claims. Based on the data given, CVM, already taking up big proportion in the total claims has also been steadily growing for the past few years. As the market is constantly growing in the pharmaceutical industry, the implication seems like CVM is a very promising field to invest in and will see more growth. Therefore, as for the sales force of the company, they should focus on securing ties with Cardiologists as they will be the ones writing most of the prescriptions.

Stacked barchart of Percentage of Cardiac vs Non-Cardiac Claims by Year

In[71]:
# Creating a new column to label "Cardiac" and "Non-Cardiac"
removed_medicare_cat_ndup['claim_type'] = removed_medicare_cat_ndup['category'].apply(lambda x: 'CVM' if x == 'Cardiac' else 'Non-CVM')

# Calculating the count of claims per year and claim type
year_claim_counts = removed_medicare_cat_ndup.groupby(['claim_year', 'claim_type']).size().unstack().fillna(0)

# Converting counts to percentages within each year
year_claim_percentages = year_claim_counts.div(year_claim_counts.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100

# Plotting the stacked bar chart
year_claim_percentages.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, figsize=(10, 6), color=['skyblue', 'salmon'])
plt.ylabel('Percentage of Claims (%)')
plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.title('Percentage of CVM vs Non-CVM Claims by Year')

# Displaying percentage labels on each segment
for i, (year, row) in enumerate(year_claim_percentages.iterrows()):
    cumulative_percentage = 0
    for claim_type, percentage in row.items():
        if percentage > 0:
            plt.text(i, cumulative_percentage + percentage / 2, f"{percentage:.1f}%", ha='center', va='center', fontsize=8)
            cumulative_percentage += percentage

plt.legend(title='Claim Type', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.xticks(rotation=0)
plt.show()

Once you perform this analysis, explain how this trend can influence the sales force deployment. That is, how would you segment the HCPs and how would you allocate In-Person (sales force) vs Non-Personal Promotions (NPP, i.e. Emails, Social Media, Digital etc.) efforts?

Analysis

Based on the data from the graph, we can easily see that the total number of provider has grown(or newly got put into the system) over the years. The number of providers with 1 CVM claims has steadily been growing in the past few years along with the number of providers with 2-4 CVM claims. We can't say the same for the group 5-9 CVM claims and 10+ CVM claims. This means that more and more prescribers are aware of the CVMs and tring the CVMs are increasing while prescribers that frequently prescribe CVMs are staying similar or not increasing as much. Since prescribers who have CVM claims over 10+ times a year is fairly rare, they should be the main focus. Of course, increasing the group of 1 CVM claim counts should be one of the goals to increase the company's customers, but the main goals should be move prescribers who is using the company's product from group 2-4 and 5-9 into 10+ group and convince prescriber who prescribes other companies in the group 10+ to use our companies product. Therefore I think that sales-force team should manage their personnels to mainly focus on maintaining or making new connections with 10+ group. Their secondary goal should focus on promoting the CVM to the 2-4 group and 5-9 group, then spend rest of the avaiable resource on expanding the influence on 1 claims group. Non-personal promotions should be done to all groups but the main focus should be on the 1 claims group as it It may become the most cost efficient ways to expand influence.

Q3. Evaluate the Patient Age demographics in the context of claim volume from 2016-2018. Bucket the patients into groups based on their age and explain the trends. How would you position the Marketing Budgets and the Promotions with respect to the changing landscape of the CVM claims and the respective patient segments?

Analysis

Based on the data given by the Stacked bar graph, other than the 2016 to 2017 in patient age 80 to 100, there has been growth in claims in all age groups between 2016 to 2018. However, even if there were larger growth percentage in the 15-59 age group, number wise, it had similar growth with 60-69 age group which had significantly lower percentage rate. This is to be expected as most of the disease pertaining to Cadrdiac are usually seen in older ages. The interesting point is that the claims from the age group of 70-79 steadily grew in pig proportions. As a result, 70-79 age group was initally smaller in claims number than 60-69, but are was larger since 2017 and became the biggest market in the age group category. As for the 80-100 age group, claims grew only in 2017-2018 by a large percentage. We can't be sure which 2016-2017 or 2017-2018 growth percentage was an excpetion. However, we must also note that age group 18-59, 60-69, and 70-79 all saw less growth percentage wise on 2017-2018 than 2016-2017. From the data given above, we can see that the market is growing in general but its rate is either similar or slowing down with expection of age group 80-100. However, due to significant growth over 2 years in 70-79 age group, they are now the major target market along with 60-69 age group. If we consider the marketing tactics, these two age group may not be as familiar with internet or cell phones as younger age group and is more used to televisions. To reach this market, the company should reach them through their HCPs (Physician Engagement programs) or through DTC Advertising and therefore marketing budget should be alloted accordingly.
